<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>keep one’s pants on • wear the pants</xh5><p> <i>keep one’s pants on</i>—<i>(coll.)</i> remain calm; keep one’s temper <i>(also: keep one’s shirt on): </i>Always remember to <u>keep your pants on</u> in times of stress.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression is not antonymous in meaning to the phrase <b>catch someone with his pants down</b>—(sl.) catch a person off guard: Rachel’s telephone call hadn’t <u>caught me with my pants down</u>.</p><p> <i>wear the pants</i>—<i>(also: wear the breeches)</i> be the dominant partner in a marriage: Mrs. Harris <u>wears the pants</u> at home: Mr. Harris is far too quiet and easy-going to argue with her.</p> </entry>
